title: Maduro to face the full wrath of American justice after narco-terrorism charges
description: Venezuela's President Nicolas Maduro has been charged with narco-terrorism after being captured by US forces.   He's currently being detained in New York and is expected to face court tomorrow.  Since he was detained, there have been hundreds of individuals both protesting and celebrating the arrest.

title: ‘Out of touch’: Littleproud blasts Albanese for ‘ignoring’ calls for Royal Commission
description: Nationals Leader David Littleproud says Prime Minister Anthony Albanese is “out of touch” for ignoring the wishes of Australians for a Bondi attack Royal Commission.

title: ‘American people pay the price’: Schumer calls Maduro’s capture reckless
description: US Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer has called US President Donald Trump’s actions in capturing Venezuelan President Nicolas Maduro reckless.  “You don’t treat lawlessness with other lawlessness, and that’s what has happened here,” he said.  “The American people pay the price in both blood and in dollar.”

title: ‘There’s not a war’: Marco Rubio denies the US is at war with Venezuela following attack
description: The US Secretary of State has denied America is at war with Venezuela following yesterday’s attack on Caracas and the capture of President Nicolas Maduro.  Speaking to NBC’s Meet the Press, Marco Rubio says Congressional approval was not needed for the attack.  “There’s not a war. I mean, we are at war against drug trafficking organisations, not a war against Venezuela,” he said.  “We will continue to reserve the right to take strikes against drug boats that are bringing drugs towards the United States that are being operated by transnational criminal organisations.”

title: ‘They’re in a lot of trouble’: Trump administration’s warning to Cuba
description: US Secretary of State Marco Rubio has warned that the Cuban government is in “a lot of trouble”.  “The Cuban government is a huge problem,” he said.  “I think they’re in a lot of trouble ... I don’t think it’s any mystery that we are not big fans of the Cuban regime.”

title: ‘Not going to give up’: Coalition to continue calls for Royal Commission in new year
description: Nationals Leader David Littleproud says the Coalition is “not going to give up” calls for a Royal Commission into the Bondi attack.  “We’re going to go back to parliament, and we’re going to prosecute the case,” Mr Littleproud told Sky News Australia.  “We do need to give answers to these families.”

title: Australian parliament set to return before Australia Day
description: Sky News Political Correspondent Cameron Reddin claims parliament is set to return before Australia Day with a “working date” for January 19.  “The Prime Minister is determined to have parliament to sit before Australia Day,” Mr Reddin told Sky News Australia.  “January 19, the working date, but that could yet change.”

title: ‘Sinister side’: Greens’ true colours tested amid calls for Royal Commission
description: Nationals Leader David Littleproud claims the Greens' true colours will be tested amid calls for a Royal Commission into the Bondi attack.  “The Greens aren’t this cute, cuddly, tree-hugging organisation they used to be, they have a sinister side,” Mr Littleproud told Sky News Australia.  “Let’s see the colour of their eyes.”

title: George Stephanopoulos embarrassingly schooled by Marco Rubio following Maduro arrest
description: US Secretary of State Marco Rubio clashed with ABC News host George Stephanopoulos following the capture of Nicolas Maduro.  On Sunday, Rubio appeared on ABC’s ‘This Week’ alongside host Stephanopoulos to discuss whether the US would run Venezuela.  On Saturday, President Donald Trump announced the US would “run the country (Venezuela)” until a safe transition of power can be arranged.  During the interview, Stephanopoulos asked Rubio what authority America had to run Venezuela following the arrest of its leader.  Rubio revealed that a “quarantine” has been placed on Venezuela’s oil until the “conditions that are in the national interest” of the US and Venezuelan people are met.  The Secretary of State added that America’s goal in Venezuela was to ensure the country would no longer be a “narco-trafficking paradise”.

title: Kristi Noem vows Maduro will ‘face the consequences’ of his crimes
description: Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem has asserted that captured Venezuelan President Nicolás Maduro will "face the consequences" of his crimes.  Noem's comments came during a Fox News Interview with Shannon Bream.  US forces captured the Venezuelan leader and his wife, Cilia Flores, in a large-scale raid on January 3.  Maduro is currently detained in New York, indicted with Narco-Terrorism Conspiracy, Cocaine Importation Conspiracy, Possession of Machineguns and Destructive Devices, and Conspiracy to Possess Machineguns and Destructive Devices against the United States.  On Saturday, the president held a press conference at Mar-a-Lago, stating that he is placing the country under temporary US control.

title: Satellite images show aftermath of US strikes on Venezuela
description: Following US military attacks in Venezuela there have been reports of civilian deaths and damage to residential buildings.  The US also targeted various military infrastructure in Caracas.  Images show the before and after of Fuerte Tiuna, the most important military complex in the country.  This comes as shoppers in Venezuela are stockpiling essentials amid fears of shortages and whether the conflict could escalate into a full-scale invasion.

title: Trump takes control of the Venezuelan oil industry after detaining President Maduro
description: US President Donald Trump has now taken control of the Venezuelan oil industry, bringing in American companies to rebuild the infrastructure.  Venezuela has the largest oil reserves on earth, with an estimated 300 billion barrels currently untapped.  The current infrastructure that has been put into place has declined due to a chronic lack of investment.

title: ‘This is not an invasion’: Marco Rubio defends America’s ‘arrest operation’ in Venezuela
description: US Secretary of State Marco Rubio has defended the US operation in Venezuela which led to the capture of Venezuelan President Nicolas Maduro.  He says it was a legal military operation, and there were limitations in notifying US lawmakers about the plan.  “This is not an invasion. We didn’t occupy a country. This was an arrest operation. This is a law enforcement operation,” Mr Rubio said.

title: Trump returns to Washington after threatening Venezuela with a second strike
description: US President Donald Trump has arrived back in Washington, DC after the successful capture of Venezuelan President Nicolas Maduro and his wife.  President Trump spent his New Year’s Eve in Mar-a-Lago, then monitored the developments on the ground during the secret operation.  The President has threatened a second strike; however, he has also stated that he does not believe it will be needed.

title: Unhinged leftists meltdown after Trump’s savage Maduro capture
description: Unhinged leftists are having a meltdown yet again.    Yes, it may be a new year but the same group of professional protesters have assembled in all corners of the globe, this time to pr otest against the US capture of Venezuelan dictator Nicolas Maduro and his wife.
